Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

1:30 PM Prosecuting attorney Chad C La Lor in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant Christopher Cline Smith II appeared by video, in custody. Attorney Ellen Denise Craker appeared by video for Christopher Cline Smith II on behalf of Attorney Rosenthal. Court calls case. Defendant verifies address. Attorney/Defendant acknowledges receipt of the complaint, waives a formal reading, enters pleas of not guilty to the misdemeanor count(s), and requests a preliminary hearing. State asks for $3,000 cash. No contact with Victim 1. Indicates he has now 4 pending felony cases in this county and has already posted over $4,%00 in this county for cash bail. State recites prior criminal history and reviews probation revocations. Defendant has had a few FTAs for cases in this county. Attorney Craker indicates that the defendant has not missed court in over 6 years. Has been in good contact with counsel and is a Superior resident. Unsure if defendant has anything to post. Court notes concerns over prior convictions, pending cases, and FTAs. Notes concerns over amount already posted in other cases and new crimes being committed. Court orders $3,000 cash. No contact with Victim 1.
Preliminary hearing scheduled for June 8, 2022 at 10:30 am.
